<hl>
<seg id=1> Advertising for Viagra, Bob Dole Appeals for Attention to Impotence </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> (New York AP) Bob Dole, Republican Presidential candidate in 1996, will take on a new activity. This time he will advertise for Pfizer, manufacturer of world-famous Viagra, to bring people's attention to the issue of sexual impotence. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> In the TV ads, Bob informed about sexual dysfunction and common men's health problems. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> Pfizer is not willing to release how much money they paid Dole, and Dole will not mention the name of Viagra. </seg>
<seg id=5> The ads will be televised at the beginning of next year. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> It is the first time Pfizer will market Viagra on TV. </seg>
<seg id=7> Pfizer is still considering whether or not the ads need a direct mention of Viagra. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=8> This May, Bob Dole admitted to having tried Viagra, and praised it highly after using, and called it a "catholicon." </seg>
<seg id=9> In his statement, Bob said, "I believe this activity may assist men in dealing with a health problem that they fear to discuss." </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=10> Since the drug entered the market this April, US doctors have written more than 6 million prescriptions for Viagra. </seg>
<seg id=11> There are 10-20 million men with sexual dysfunction, only 10% of whom seek a doctor's advice. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=12> Dole had been on a discussion program and urged citizens to diagnose and treat prostate cancer and realize its side-effect, impotence. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=13> Dole was diagnosed with prostate cancer in 1991. Doctors said he recovered after the treatments. </seg>
</p>
